Notes: Feeling ok today. Just experiencing some nausea.
Feeling quite ok today. No complaints.

RelaxText1: Taking a break may mean being very active. It may mean not doing very much at all.
RelaxText2: Take a deep breath… and relax. Try reading a book, yoga or meditation, or just putting your feet up.
RelaxText3: Listen to your body. If you’re really tired, give yourself time to sleep.
RelaxText4: Without good sleep, our mental health suffers and our concentration goes downhill.

TalkText1: If it feels awkward at first, give it time.
TalkText2: Make talking about your feelings something that you do.
TalkText3: Talking about your feelings isn’t a sign of weakness.
TalkText4: It’s part of taking charge of your wellbeing and doing what you can to stay healthy.
TalkText5: Talking can be a way to cope with a problem you’ve been carrying around in your head for a while.
TalkText6: Just being listened to can help you feel supported and less alone.
TalkText7: And it works both ways. If you open up, it might encourage others to do the same.

AcceptText2: It’s much healthier to accept that you’re unique than to wish you were more like someone else
AcceptText3: Feeling good about yourself boosts your confidence to learn new skills, visit new places and make new friends.
AcceptText4: Good self-esteem helps you cope when life takes a difficult turn.

ExerciseText1: Experts believe exercise releases chemicals in your brain that make you feel good.
ExerciseText2: Regular exercise can boost your self-esteem and help you concentrate, sleep and feel better.
ExerciseText3: Exercising doesn’t just mean doing sport or going to the gym.
ExerciseText4: Walks in the park, gardening or housework can also keep you active.
ExerciseText5: Experts say most people should do about 30 minutes’ exercise at least five days a week.
ExerciseText6: Try to make physical activity that you enjoy a part of your day.
ExerciseText7: Helps you feel good and maintain your health.

FoodText1: Strong links between what we eat and how we feel.
FoodText2: Eat at least three meals each day and drink plenty of water.
FoodText3: Try to limit how many high-caffeine or sugary drinks you have, and avoid too much alcohol.
FoodText4: But food can also have a long-lasting effect on your mental health.
FoodText5: Your brain needs a mix of nutrients to stay healthy and function well, just like the other organs in your body.

HelpText1: Don't be worried or afraid to talk to a physician or therapist
HelpText2: None of us are superhuman. We all sometimes get tired or overwhelmed by how we feel or when things go wrong.
HelpText3: If things are getting too much for you and you feel you can’t cope, ask for help.
